Protocol.text: All microarrays were scanned on a GenePix 4000B Microarray Scanner (Axon Instruments, Union City, CA, USA). For each microarray individual laser power and photomultiplier settings were used, allowing all signals to remain in the linear range of the scanner. Separate scan images for Cy3 and Cy5 were produced
The mice were fed on a standard diet and left untreated
We housed all mice for eight weeks prior to analysis.

RNA preparation. At tissue harvest we immediately placed samples in RNAlater (Ambion) for storage prior to processing. We later transferred the tissues from RNAlater, submerged them in 5 ml Trizol (Invitrogen) and homogenized 3 times for 20 seconds using a Polytron PT2100 (Novodirect). We extracted the RNA according to the manufacturer’s instructions (Trizol/Invitrogen).

Fluorescent cDNA probes were synthesized from 5 µg total RNA using a linear mRNA amplification protocol, exactly as described in (http://cmgm.stanford.edu/pbrown/protocols/ampprotocol_3.html). 3µg of the T7 RNA polymerase amplified antisense RNA was subsequently subjected to a direct labeling reaction by incorporation of Cy3 fluorescent dyes using random primers (http://cmgm.stanford.edu/pbrown/protocols/4_human_RNA.html).

Fluorescent cDNA probes were synthesized from 5 µg total RNA using a linear mRNA amplification protocol, exactly as described in (http://cmgm.stanford.edu/pbrown/protocols/ampprotocol_3.html). 3µg of the T7 RNA polymerase amplified antisense RNA was subsequently subjected to a direct labeling reaction by incorporation of Cy5 fluorescent dyes using random primers (http://cmgm.stanford.edu/pbrown/protocols/4_human_RNA.html).

The microarrays were immersed at 42°C in 6xSSC/0,5%SDS/1%BSA for 40 min and subsequently washed extensively with ddH2O at room temperature. Prior to hybridization, the spotted PCR products were denatured by immersing the slides at 95°C in ddH2O for 2 min. Excess of liquid was removed from the slides by centrifuging them briefly at 715xg in a microtiter plate centrifuge (Z320, Hermle, Wehingen, Germany). Prior to hybridization, the purified Cy3 and Cy5 labeled cDNAs were mixed, 5 µg poly(dA) and 1 µg human Cot1 DNA (both Gibco Invitrogen Corp., Carlsbad, Ca, USA) were added and subsequently evaporated in a vacuum Concentrator 5301 (Eppendorf, Hamburg, Germany) at 60°C. The resulting pellet was dissolved in 12 µl hybridization buffer (50% formamide / 6xSSC / 0,5%SDS / 5x Denhardt) and denatured by incubating at 95°C for 2 min. The probe was then transferred onto the array under a 24x24 mm coverslip and incubated in a humid chamber (GeneMachines, San Carlos, CA, USA) containing 2xSSC drops for providing humidity. Hybridization was performed for 12h to 16h in a 42°C waterbath (GFL, Burgwedel, Germany). After hybridization the microarrays were washed in 0,1xSSC / 0,1%SDS for 10 min and twice with 0,1xSSC for 5 min (on an orbital shaker), followed by a brief immersion of the slides in ddH2O. Finally, the washed slides were dried by centrifuging them briefly at 715xg in a microtiter plate centrifuge (Z320, Hermle, Wehingen, Germany). All washing steps were performed at room temperature.

Induction of secondary iron overload. We induced secondary iron overload in 129S6/SvEvTac mice by intraperitoneal administration of five (5) mg of iron dextran (100 mL of a 50 mg/mL solution) twice a week during weeks 5-7 of the study (six doses total). We sacrificed animals for analysis at eight weeks of age.

Induction of iron deficiency. We fed an iron-deficient diet (C-1038, Altromin, Lage, Germany) to C57BL/6 mice for three weeks immediately after weaning. We sacrificed these animals at 7 weeks of age for analysis.

Description.text: We determined duodenal and liver gene response patterns in mice with primary (Hfe –/– and C282Y homozygous mice) and secondary iron overload versus 129S6/SvEvTac wild type controls.

BibliographicReference.title: Regulatory defects in liver and intestine implicate abnormal hepcidin and Dcytb expression in murine hemochromatosis
